That’ll do, fall. That’ll do. 

We’ve been enjoying our late-afternoon walks and mostly spend the entire time in disbelief that we get to enjoy this. Friendly neighbors say hello; there was even a dad in a Santa hat last night pushing a stroller. We passed two little girls in Christmas dresses racing from tree to tree in the park. An elderly neighbor dressed all in red and green was outside sweeping her leaves and told us Truman was a very cute dog. Anja slept in her bassinet. 

How any of this is real is the greatest gift and mystery.

The home of Jan Barboglio 🤍 

A lot of wish we could be so lucky as to have a specific vision and drive. That when you’ve placed your mark on something, it’s unmistakable whose work was at hand. The home of @janbarboglio is a stunning work of art in itself, but the true gift is feeling embraced by every corner of the atmosphere with true intention in genuine soul. 

Every chair, every painting, every fixture, and every texture. Curated by an artist whose life is poured into her unmistakable and exquisite work. 

Just after our first shoot at her home, I sent a few snaps to my mom and sister in awe of the home itself. Without any additional details, my sister immediately texted back from her home in California, “Is that Jan’s house?!” (She’s a big fan.)

Sometimes it feels like we need to be tied to an aesthetic — a color scheme, a fashion trend, a tiktok niche, a font…
We don’t. But when you give yourself the opportunity to live and explore what is authentically you, beauty comes forward and your “aesthetic” is truly a life well lived and loved.

2023 here we come 🎉

“Processing.” Our sweet Anja is almost 2 months old, and I’m soaking up every coo and cry, snuggle and nuzzle. We’ve settled into a nice, natural routine, and I get excited every time I see her little face. 

When she was first born, though, all I could articulate was that I was processing. I heard so many people say, “I could never have imagined I’d love someone this much..” or “I didn’t know my heart could feel like this…” … things that make so much sense, but they just weren’t thoughts that came into my head. All I could offer was turning to Andrew and saying, “I’m processing.”

I also sat in bed on the third day in the hospital and looked at photos of Truman and cried because I missed my dog….

And now I’ve processed, and I’ve come to know her better, and our little family feels so full of the sweetest unconditional love I’ve always hoped for. 

So here’s the first post of 2023. The best day of my life was the best day of my life… it just took me a while to process it. And that’s okay 🤍

As a product of the 90s, there are a few things — on brand or not — that I happen to love: The Secret Garden, Toaster Strudel, and Summer Olympics are three of them. This shoot concept by @nastialiukin and set by @bottegadeflores brought me right back into a space where things can be colorful and dreamy, soft and lovely, confident and powerful. Fitting, we ended cleanup with a Spice Girls dance party.
The definitive argument winner of “summer vs winner” — COATS. Winter has coats. Done. Winter wins. ❄️

Some nights simply call for a martini 🍸 … we don’t make the rules 🤷🏻‍♀️ we just imbibe by them.

“It’s a season,” I keep telling myself, after wearing the same pajamas for days on end and donning spit up in places I can’t even see. It’s a season. Do I miss traveling, squeezing as many cities into one month as possible? Of course. But do I love this season of staying close to home, making sacrifices to our family first, and taking things a little bit slower? Absolutely. But I also cannot wait to start taking the family on trips and discovering the world through a brand new way of viewing it.
#webrunch

Getting back into the swing of things after having Anja in November, and just now got around to developing this roll of film. Oh, the little moments I had forgotten I’d taken. ☺️ Of course, @ashleyrobertson, CEO extraordinaire doing touch ups for her own makeup line shoot, making sure everything had that personal touch to make the vision come to fruition. 

I was 8 months pregnant at this shoot… not looking cute, definitely not feeling cute, but this day was such a blast and reinvigorated why it is that I do what I do. It was a full-day shoot, and I remember wondering HOW on earth I was going to do it. But as with anything, we just do it. Pray, hope, and don’t worry. 

I saw something recently — “I wonder what David was thinking before he faced Goliath; I wonder how Moses’s mom felt before putting him in the basket…” imagine if they had known BEFORE how it would have turned out. … Live with faith and trust in God like you know it’s going to turn out great. 

This day wasn’t some huge looking anxiety cloud. In fact, I was really excited about it and looking forward to it. Regardless, I was also proud of myself for committing and knowing that we’d do it and it’d be great, and it was. 🤍
Sweet simplicity 🤍 need a bigger house to gather up all the stunning home decor

This week has been an accidental but welcomed practice in waking up a little earlier, doing a little bit more, focusing a little more diligently. Not worrying about “having enough energy” but knowing God will provide, and that we can always find joy in humbling ourselves and pouring ourselves out for others. 

“Strong reasons make strong actions. … Hell is full of the talented, but Heaven, of the energetic.” Venerable Archbishop Fulton Sheen

Camera dump for spring 🌸 

Honestly, …. Honestly? This morning I had my finger so heavily hovering over the “deactivate account” button, only to be briefly distracted enough by the thought that I’m not 100% sure i remember my password to ever log back in. 

While there are still incredible shoots I’m on and people I’m working with, I feel like the things that are really dear to me that I want to share, aren’t things that I want to share on this platform. 

I don’t think my baby’s face needs to be for everyone to see; the giggles of my nieces aren’t for everyone’s ears; the glow of a clean home after a long day isn’t for everyone to appreciate. 

There’s just too much. Being too close to the social media world makes it all seem so consumable — so “shoppable.” So “here’s my life so you can buy these things off Amazon”. My proximity is to blame. I expose myself to so much of it. But it’s not even a hard tightrope to walk — it’s a hard tightrope to FIND.
Suddenly craving a martini for some reason 🍸

What a beautiful morning exploring Madison Sézane at @lesolhouse. The first time I bought @sezane was just before a trip to Rome, and I felt so *European* in anything but blue jeans and a t-shirt. It’s truly been my go-to treat for myself for years and I was elated to meet their team and have a peak of their new Éditions collection 🤍
Give me food, a full bar, and room to play and I’m happy. Sando party down in @midnightramblerbar — you’ve never seen smiles like these when sandos are being slung and drinks are flowing 🍸

Last week was busy with events back to back to back. At most of these at least one person asks me “what do you mostly shoot?” It was a surprise to me when I realized how heavy my calendar is with curated events, but in my head, this is what I do. ☁️ Portraits that breathe. People in places. Collaboration. This was the vision that came to me in 2014. Letting every detail be intentional and letting the personality come through. A little studio, natural light, and human connection.

Morning coffee in the morning chair enjoying the quiet and finally nearing finishing the book I’ve been reading for the last three years. (I’m simply not an avid reader, but I’m practicing.)

It seems like spring days are all-or-nothing. They’re either full of inspiration met with immediate action; or they are nonsense and you just have to do your best to make it through the day. But I’ve always said, springtime in Dallas is a magical time. It’s when so much synergy happens — simply leave your home and good things will happen. You’ll bump into the right people, you’ll be in the right place at the right time, things will come to you that you could have never planned or anticipated.

 I have no guess was to why this is true, but it is. And I’m so thankful to God for bringing me to this place, in this time, with these people… Things seem crazy, but there is still so much to be thankful for.

Quick catch up since I feel like my cadence in posting has changed quite a bit in the last year. 

I had a baby girl in November 2022 (I’m still bumping into people who had no idea i was ever pregnant — I wasn’t big on posting about it a ton 😉). Since mid-February I’ve been back shooting with clients but my hours are pretty much limited to just a couple mornings and some evenings. As a 30-something People Pleaser, it’s great being able to look at my calendar, have set hours, and tell myself, “No, Becca, you can’t just fill every open space.. you’ve filled your slots for this week, it’s okay to tell people you’re booked.” It’s taken me HOW many years to get to this place?! But some lessons are learned the hard way and take about 8 years and 10 months to finally solidify. 

Anja is great. I’ve taken her to plenty of shoots; everyone has been so generous and helpful and welcoming towards our new normal. It means a lot. I’ll leave it at that. You know who you are. It means a lot. 🤍 

It’s been hard discerning what to share and what not to share. The typical “BECKLEY” pace has changed — life is slower. Less travel. Less full days of shoots. I’ve given myself permission to live fully in the present. (I’m still like every other doting parent who over-photographs their child). But I’ve found myself so reluctant to let the internet into our lives in a way that would mean showing her more often. It’s been hard. I’m someone who is happy when I’m creating and sharing. So it’s felt disjointed to not feel comfortable sharing as freely and as often as I used to. Less of my life is “on brand.” And what a funny thing to ever even consider. Most of my clothes don’t fit; I’m not out and about the same way; I’m not inspired by recent travels; I don’t have time to sit around and wait for inspiration. 

And this isn’t to be confused with upset. These are just candid thoughts I’ve had for so long, without knowing exactly how or if I wanted to share them. But I do, and I hope I can continue to share with this little community. I think I’m just trying to find my new footing

Life lately. I’ve been scrolling through photos since Anja was born and it felt like everything I’ve been posting has been so tightly-wound. Like I couldn’t let go and just share reality. I’ve always had the (can barely qualify as) philosophy of sharing reality… in my own way. It doesn’t have to be EVERYTHING. Little bits though, in my own way, that share how I see it for other people to see it. 

But after Anja was born and I was looking through all the wonderful memories since then, versus what I’ve shared… why didn’t I just share some of these real moments? Yes, they’re precious and I don’t want to over-share Anja herself, but there were so many times I only shared when I thought things looked more “perfect” and that’s just not me. 

There’s grace to give myself in navigating changes. There’s literally everything that’s more important than what goes on social media. But there’s your real-talk insta-blog upstate for you 🤍

I think most things in life are like avocados… or bananas… If you’re waiting for just the right time to do something, you’re going to miss it. I think a lot of us feel like we need to be responsible, or “do it the right way,” and I don’t disagree… but what if some things just work themselves out? Maybe it’s impossible for us to be perfect, and maybe just going out and DOING, and LIVING is actually the best we could ever do?

Daily reminders during the summertime drop in inspiration. Shooting these with Brooke was the exact creative collaboration I needed 🤍

1. Do something just for the fun of it.
"Something" can be your craft or something entirely different. Go out and take photos with a friend (which is where these images happen to come from). Go to a concert. Unplug and cook a meal and drink GOOD wine and listen to music.  Take a load off. Just enjoy life, enjoy the moments, and inspiration will come back to you without you hunting it down and hoping it will surrender and come crawling back. 

2. Read magazines.
Get off Instagram. It's a life ruiner. It ruins people's lives. Look to the professionals. They know what they're doing. Immerse yourself in quality writing, curated images and styles. We all know it's hard not to compare yourself to whomever you follow on Instagram, so opt to look elsewhere for inspiration. Magazines are beautiful works of art that deserve more of our attention. 

3. Pick your head up.
Whatever you're doing, you're doing great. It's easier said than done, but don't compare yourself. Look up from your usual field of vision and see your work from what it is. Want to change? Fine. Want to improve? Go for it. Do you need to slow down? Do it. It's rarely a case of all-of-a sudden we think everything we've done is complete trash, but it's normal to see areas where we can improve. So acknowledge that and give yourself some time to figure out what that is. (Continued in comments)

LIVE SIMPLY
BY PADRE PIO
Live simply. Eat simply. Love one another simply. Do not complicate matters unnecessarily. How do you live simply? You remove activities that are not necessary or that pull away from your duty. Do not think, my friends, that you live in a world where the need for simplicity has disappeared. There should be calm and if there is not calm in your life, change your life and keep changing it until you feel calm. The act of sitting and reading these words is forcing you to consider heaven's wishes for you. Pull yourself away from the world even further and spend some time in silence. Ask Jesus to show you which activities should be removed. Live Simply.

Pray, hope, and don’t worry. 
St. Padre Pio, pray for us

I’ve been stuck in how to pursue a career while walking in humility. I’ve been stuck finding the right way to share while maintaining appropriate privacy. I’ve been stuck watching things move forward while still processing the past. But fall is here, and so of course, somehow clarity rested upon me this morning in “share.” Just “share.” Share it. Share it. Welcome people to walk through this with you. 

There are existential things I’ve been stuck on lately. … God stuff… good stuff. And there was a line recently.. something about if you seek wisdom, then read wisdom (if you know the verse, please share.) But it was so humbling. I’d been mulling over these things that I simply don’t have the answers to. Ask. Ask God. Read the Bible. Talk about it…. Ask. 

I don’t have all the answers, or any answers. But I do have this beautiful fall day that is absolutely perfect.

I think what we get tripped up on is “correct.” You can be a “correct” photographer without being a “good” photographer; and you can be a “good” photographer without being a “correct” photographer. What does “correct” even mean? In literature, we experience the author’s ability to paint a picture, or evoke a mood. We don’t just fall in love with a novel because of how “correct” it is or how perfect the grammar is. Though, so many techniques and intentionality often lie behind the effortless prose. So, to be “correct” or not “correct”? Yes. Just be.

My friend and I played hooky, got brunch,  and walked around Bishop Arts. (This was when the area was still only about two blocks by two blocks). We walked into Jackson Vaughn and smelled every candle in there. It felt so real, so welcoming, so sophisticated and artistic and beautiful. Curated and full, organized and peaceful. 

In college I was studying to become a physical therapist, but always reading blogs, browsing Pinterest and tumblr, and upvoting on that street style website that I can’t remember the name of. If someone would have told that girl that she’d be photographing for them, she never would have believed it. 

It’s been a treasure to see their vision evolve and collections grow, and to get to know the artists behind the brand and see their vision flourish 🤍

All I can think to share is “Man, God is so so good. Please pray for me, and I’ll be praying for you too.” Through a series of beautiful events, I had the pleasure of going out to California to photograph an event with Fr. Mike Schmitz. Maybe you’ve heard of him, maybe you haven’t. Many people, across all walks of life, have come to listen to his homilies, his Bible in a Year Podcast, his Catechism in a Year… it’s incredible the breadth and depth to which he reaches people. He always signs off asking that we all pray for each other, and, while we are all faced with the big, huge, giant question of, “WHAT do we do?! WHAT can we do?!” He continues to share the message of love. As simple as that. Of God’s infinite love for us, and that we, as disciples of Christ, are called to love. 

A few people picked up on my pure joy as I photographed the crowd of people eager to say hello to him and share just a sliver of how he has impacted their lives. As he looked everyone in the eye, and truly embraced each meeting, I stood by, giddy to be among so many truly happy people. Now, happy doesn’t mean delusional; happy means thankful, it means sacrifice of self, it means thanking God for the blessings AND the suffering. I joked we should have titled the event, “Hi, I know you!” because of the way everyone felt they had already welcomed Fr. Mike into their lives.

And the beauty that all this comes down to, is his ability to share Christ’s light with the world. Fr. Mike is on a fundraising mission to build a church that is so badly needed where he is based at The Newman Center at University of Minnesota Duluth. 

It’s not about one person, though we were so blessed to meet, listen to, and spend time with Fr. Mike; we are all called to be saints, to answer God’s call, and to love the person in front of you, and that’s what he preaches. 

What an honor to photograph this event and mass. Good things are happening.

How I take videos as a photographer (both on iPhone and camera)

1. Keep the movement to a minimum
2. Have the subject enter the frame, exit the frame, or be doing a small motion (leaves rustling, candle flickering, coffee in milk swirling)
3. Keep the main subject as close to the center as possible for reels and stories
4. When editing clips together, trim the clips shorter than you think is necessary, really getting the juicy nugget of what you want to show 
5. Only use a gimbal if you really need it. Most of the time it just slows me down and makes me tired. 
6. Play around with the 2x or 3x feature on your phone. It can add a more cinematic feel. (Or use cinema mode if you’re rocking a fancy phone like that)

We’re back, baby 🤍

How many times in this last year have I repeated, “This feels like the good old days of 2017.” The community, the bumping into people when you’re out and about, the growth, the regrowth… 2023 may not have been the best year for many of us, but what I witnessed was a breath of fresh air. Finally returning to a point of normalcy that wasn’t just “normalcy.” It felt like the spark came back for many of us. Moving pieces, collaborative projects, challenges and milestones. 

The return of Mirador was a highlight of that feeling of being “back.” Walking in and seeing familiar faces — the team back together again. It felt good. It felt like a victory. I used to be working up at Mirador often photographing new menu items, tasting dinners, cocktails…

On the plane ride home, I mentioned to Andrew that I think we’ve both been blessed with appreciating life more often than not. Most likely thanks to our upbringing, we both assume nothing is owed to us and are sincerely grateful for whatever life brings us. Some situations are more challenging than others, but we both were blessed with the ability to take it in stride and still pretty much only see the positives in life. Late nights at work, busy season, things not going according to plans, bonks, hiccups, adjustments… home things, life things… 

What’s amazing is that I feel like I’ve witnessed the same in the people we choose to surround ourselves with. In a word (or two): positivity and gratefulness. Maybe that adds up to humility, but I’ll always be afraid of labeling myself “humble” lest I stand proudly on that assumption.

With time away from work to have the space to reflect, it felt good to come home excited for the new year. When you’re not constantly playing catch-up, so much more seems possible, and I wonder why I ever felt uninspired for under-motivated. I felt that deep-rooted energy, that force that drives you towards your passion. I could see the “BECKLEY” vision again. I decided it’s time to get back to action rather than timidly “planning” for years on end. 

But then I got home. 10pm after a long day of travel I was playing with my daughter in her room and thought, “yea ok but what if I just want to be a stay at home mom? This pace feels right.” 

So I reflected on my vision of BECKLEY — the one I saw so clearly in 2014. There’s an energy to it, it’s peaceful but kind of fast-paced at the same time. And then there’s motherhood. No need to rush anything, seeing the world through my daughter’s eyes. 

What if the dream of who I’d become, of how I envisioned my “perfect, grown-up, successful self” is already here? What if the person I envisioned myself becoming is already here. Complete in motherhood, and work, and family, and friends. What if this complex mix and balance is even more perfect than what my younger self could have ever imagined for me?

This is the Upload/Culling Process that has worked well for me over the years. Of course, everyone has their own work flow, but this is helped me keep projects organized while working on multiple shoots at the same time. 

1. Upload all RAW images to external hard drive. Make a separate folder “UPLOAD” and then add a subfolder for each shoot “[DATE][CLIENT]”
2. Rename all images (Select All > Right Click > Rename) “[DATE][YOUR BUSINESS NAME][CLIENT NAME]” 
3. Cull photos in Narrative Select or Photo Mechanic (if using PM, create a separate folder in hard drive called “Photo Mechanic Upload” and select as the destination folder)
4. Ship selected images to Lightroom and create new album “[DATE][CLIENT NAME]”
5. Edit and export with desired settings.

For too long, I keep telling myself to go back to 2018 — that’s what I consider my peak. But why? To “find my voice”? I felt like if i tapped back into the BECKLEY voice, I’d be more sure of what I had to say. But I don’t think it ever was a “voice.” I think it a writer, a narrator, a composer. It was letting my thoughts flow straight into words in a journal in my mind. Writing is something I’ve “meant to do” for so long, and I truly feel it calm my racing thoughts, encourage composure, and allow space to THINK your own thoughts clearly.

Honestly, this is what got things started in the first place. Tumblr days, reading blogs, browsing street style, falling in love with photos from magazines, one at a time. Life was a little slower and a little juicier. There was time to curate, to cultivate, before moving on to the next “aesthetic.” 

But that was the original vision. DOING the things that I wanted photographed. Not faking it for a photo. DOING it. MAKING the memories, not faking them.

We called it “La La Land.” A way of seeing the world in a completely romanticized way. Music helps. Always music, always a soundtrack. Keeping things clean helps. The right scents do it too. The right outfit. (Not a *new* outfit clothes always, but appreciating what you have and seeing with newly inspired eyes to make something new.)
Community is where it’s at. We’d be nothing without our Dallas family.
